INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8188d25a-17e4-4565-9238-548e4a5dc55f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$pandas at Scale — Chunking, Sampling, and Knowing When to Leave$escape$,
  $escape$When pd.read_csv() throws MemoryError, your first instinct shouldn't be more RAM. Use the chunksize parameter to stream DataFrames in fixed-size pieces, applying aggregations incrementally. For column-heavy files, pass usecols to drop irrelevant columns at parse time — this alone can cut memory 60%+.

For exploratory work, sample before you commit. df.sample(frac=0.05) gives you a statistically useful subset. Pair it with df.memory_usage(deep=True).sum() to track actual memory footprint, especially with object-dtype columns that hide bloated string allocations.

When chunking isn't enough, Dask wraps the pandas API in lazy, partitioned execution — same syntax, parallel compute. It shines between 1–100GB. Beyond that, you're fighting Python's GIL and serialization overhead.

The graduation signal to Spark: when your data lives in distributed storage (S3/HDFS), needs fault-tolerant cluster execution, or your Dask task graph serialization time rivals compute time. pandas is the right tool until it isn't — and chunking extends that threshold further than most expect.$escape$,
  $escape$import pandas as pd

# Stream a large CSV in 50k-row chunks
chunks = pd.read_csv(
    "events.csv",
    chunksize=50_000,
    usecols=["user_id", "event", "timestamp"],
    dtype={"user_id": "int32", "event": "category"},
    parse_dates=["timestamp"],
)

daily_counts = pd.DataFrame()
for chunk in chunks:
    agg = chunk.groupby(chunk["timestamp"].dt.date)["event"].count()
    daily_counts = pd.concat([daily_counts, agg])

result = daily_counts.groupby(daily_counts.index).sum()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
