INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a469fe9c-98fd-4f08-bc6e-07397d93d0d1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$pandas DataFrame Hashing — Version Your Datasets With pd.util.hash_pandas_object$escape$,
  $escape$Every model checkpoint deserves a pinned dataset fingerprint. Without it, you can't reproduce results or audit drift. pandas gives you `pd.util.hash_pandas_object()`, which returns a per-row hash Series using the underlying block values — not Python `hash()`, so it's stable across sessions.

Compute a single dataset fingerprint by combining row hashes with `hashlib`. Store this alongside your model metadata (MLflow params, DVC `.dvc` files, or a simple JSON manifest). When you reload a DataFrame for retraining, recompute and compare — a mismatch means schema drift, new rows, or silent column-type coercion.

Key gotchas: `hash_pandas_object` is sensitive to dtype. A column read as `int64` vs `Int64` (nullable) produces different hashes. Always call `df.convert_dtypes()` or enforce a schema with `df.astype()` before hashing. Also, column order matters — sort with `df[sorted(df.columns)]` for canonical ordering. Pair this with `df.describe().to_json()` for a human-readable stats snapshot per version.$escape$,
  $escape$import hashlib
import pandas as pd

def fingerprint(df: pd.DataFrame) -> str:
    df = df[sorted(df.columns)].convert_dtypes()
    row_hashes = pd.util.hash_pandas_object(df)
    combined = hashlib.sha256(row_hashes.values.tobytes()).hexdigest()
    return combined

df = pd.read_csv("training_data.csv")
version_hash = fingerprint(df)
print(f"Dataset version: {version_hash[:12]}")
# Store version_hash in your model registry or manifest.json$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
